english:
  title: Written at Yunam Temple
  author: Chen Hua
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Last night a single branch of mountain plum came into bloom,
    yet the old monks dwelling there knew not to gather it.
    Young official, your heart is full of tender feeling—
    you wander through the cold thicket seeking its news.

    I lament we have no jade flutes of the immortals
    to blow away the sorrows of this distant parting.
    Three days I've stayed upon the mountain without climbing high,
    unable to escape the bite of the eastern wind.

    Tomorrow at dawn I mount my horse toward the red dust of the world.
    Who will linger to admire the moon through the hall's silk curtains?
  footnotes:
    - 'Yunam Temple: A mountain temple in classical Korea, representing a place of spiritual refuge and natural beauty.'
    - The mountain plum (梅) symbolizes resilience and quiet beauty in East Asian poetry, blooming in harsh conditions.
    - The 'red dust' (紅塵) is a classical metaphor for the mundane, worldly realm with all its attachments and suffering, contrasted with the purity of mountain temples.
